# SPYRAL OS — Local Development Environment Variables
# Copy this to .env.local and fill in the values.
# .env.local is gitignored — your secrets stay local.

# Authentication
# IMPORTANT: In production (Vercel), set AUTH_SECRET in the Vercel project dashboard:
#   Settings → Environment Variables → AUTH_SECRET
# Generate a secret using:
#   node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('hex'))"
# AUTH_SECRET=

# If AUTH_SECRET is not set:
#   - In production: a stable fallback is derived from VERCEL_GIT_REPO_SLUG + OWNER
#   - In development: a deterministic secret is derived from the machine hostname
#   Both ensure tokens survive server restarts and redeploys.
#   For maximum security, always set AUTH_SECRET explicitly.

# Session Persistence (Production)
# For production on Vercel, user data is stored in a JSON file (/tmp/spyral-data/).
# However, /tmp/ is ephemeral on serverless — it can be cleared between requests.
# To make user accounts persist reliably, add a Redis database:
#
#   1. Go to Vercel Dashboard → Storage → Create Database → Redis (Upstash)
#   2. Follow the integration steps (the free tier works fine)
#   3. Vercel automatically injects these environment variables:
#      UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL, UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN
#
# With Redis configured, users stay registered even after serverless cold starts.
# Without Redis, signups will work but logins may fail after /tmp/ is cleared.
#
# For local development, a JSON file is used automatically (no Redis needed).
# To test Redis locally, set these variables:
# UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL=
# UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN=
